In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To override, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Detect current theme
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI or rebind styles here
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Using it in a page/view-model:**

```csharp
public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ApplyTheme(Application.Current.RequestedTheme);
        Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() => ApplyTheme(e.RequestedTheme));
    }

    void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        BackgroundColor = theme == AppTheme.Dark
            ? Colors.Black
            : Colors.White;
    }
}
```

**Declarative approach in XAML** (automatically responds to theme changes):

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

**Key points:**

| API | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `RequestedTheme` | Read the current system theme |
| `RequestedThemeChanged` | React to OS-level toggles in real time |
| `UserAppTheme` | Force a theme; set to `Unspecified` to follow system |
| `AppThemeBinding` | XAML markup that auto-switches per theme |

`AppThemeBinding` handles most UI cases declaratively. Use the event for side effects like logging or syncing preferences.
